```json
{
  "application": "slurm",
  "details": {
    "job_name": "osu-micro-benchmarks@5.7.1",
    "account": "use300",
    "reservation": "root_63",
    "partition": "ind-shared",
    "nodes": 1,
    "tasks_per_node": 1,
    "cpus_per_task": 16,
    "memory": "32G",
    "time": "00:30:00",
    "output": "%x.o%j.%N",
    "scheduler_module": "slurm",
    "spack_version": "0.17.2",
    "spack_instance_name": "cpu",
    "spack_instance_dir": "/cm/shared/apps/spack/0.17.2/cpu",
    "spack_package": "osu-micro-benchmarks@5.7.1",
    "spack_compiler": "gcc@10.2.0",
    "spack_variants": "~cuda",
    "spack_dependencies": "^openmpi@4.1.3/$(spack find --format '{hash:7}' openmpi@4.1.3 % ${SPACK_COMPILER})",
    "spack_spec": "osu-micro-benchmarks@5.7.1 % gcc@10.2.0 ~cuda ^openmpi@4.1.3/$(spack find --format '{hash:7}' openmpi@4.1.3 % gcc@10.2.0)",
    "dependent_script": "netlib-scalapack@2.1.0.sh"
  }
}
```

The script is running on a Slurm cluster. It is using Spack, a package manager for scientific software, to install and manage the `osu-micro-benchmarks` package. The script also defines a number of environment variables, including the name of the system, the version and instance of Spack, and the specific version of the `osu-micro-benchmarks` package. The script then uses Spack to install the `osu-micro-benchmarks` package. Once the installation is complete, the script uses `sbatch` to submit a job that runs a separate script, `netlib-scalapack@2.1.0.sh`.
